"guideline_excerpts": [{"text": "Code the cardiac procedure documented: a complete transthoracic echocardiogram with Doppler is 93306; a routine 12-lead ECG with interpretation is 93000. Append modifier 26 when only the physician's interpretation is performed at a facility. Code the cardiac diagnosis/indication (e.g., heart failure, valvular disease, arrhythmia); use a sign/symptom when no definitive diagnosis is established.", "source": "Cardiology Coding Guidance", "section": "Procedures"}, {"text": "Modifier 26 reports the professional component (the physician's interpretation); modifier TC the technical component (equipment/technologist). For a radiologist's interpretation of imaging performed at a facility (POS 22 outpatient hospital, 23 emergency room), append modifier 26.", "source": "Radiology Coding Guidance", "section": "Components"}, {"text": "When a combined study code exists (e.g., CT abdomen and pelvis), report the single combination code rather than the individual component codes.", "source": "Radiology Coding Guidance", "section": "Combination"}, {"text": "Surgical pathology CPT (88300-88309) is selected by specimen and complexity level; a skin specimen examined microscopically is typically level IV (88305). Append modifier 26 for the pathologist's professional interpretation at a facility.", "source": "Pathology Coding Guidance", "section": "Levels"}, {"text": "Code the OB/GYN service documented: obstetric ultrasound (>=14 weeks, transabdominal) = 76805; colposcopy of the cervix with biopsy = 57454; endometrial biopsy = 58100; IUD insertion = 58300. For routine pregnancy supervision, use Z34.8x by trimester (not an O-code) when uncomplicated. Code cervical dysplasia to specificity (CIN I = N87.0, CIN II = N87.1). When one provider gives antepartum + delivery + postpartum care, use the global obstetric package (e.g., 59400) rather than itemizing visits.", "source": "OB/GYN Coding Guidance", "section": "Procedures"}]}, {"hard": false, "notes": "Coding notes: (1) I48.91 is assigned as principal diagnosis because atrial fibrillation was definitively diagnosed by ECG findings (irregularly irregular rhythm, absent P waves, fibrillatory baseline) and confirmed in the impression. The documentation does not specify whether this is paroxysmal, persistent, or permanent atrial fibrillation, so the unspecified code is appropriate. (2) R00.2 (palpitations) is coded as secondary because it was the presenting symptom/indication for the study and is documented separately from the diagnosis. (3) CPT 93000 is assigned for the complete routine 12-lead ECG with interpretation and report. No modifier 26 is appended because the chart does not specify that this was performed at a facility (POS 22/23) with only the professional component being billed; the documentation suggests a complete service. (4) No documentation of irregular pulse as a separately codable diagnosis beyond the palpitations and confirmed atrial fibrillation. (5) High confidence on all codes due to clear documentation and direct match to candidate codes.", "stage": "3_coding", "title": "Code Candidate Generation", "samples": 1, "candidates": [{"code": "I48.91", "role": "principal", "sequence": 1, "modifiers": [], "_agreement": 1.0, "confidence": 0.95, "code_system": "ICD10CM", "description": "Unspecified atrial fibrillation", "chart_citations": [{"text": "Atrial fibrillation with controlled ventricular response", "section": "IMPRESSION", "line_end": 5, "line_start": 5}, {"text": "Irregularly irregular rhythm with absent P waves and fibrillatory baseline; ventricular rate 92 bpm", "section": "FINDINGS", "line_end": 4, "line_start": 4}], "rule_justification": "Definitive diagnosis of atrial fibrillation established by ECG findings and physician impression; principal diagnosis per cardiology guidelines.", "guideline_citations": [{"text": "Code the cardiac diagnosis/indication (e.g., heart failure, valvular disease, arrhythmia); use a sign/symptom when no definitive dia