sabdominal) = 76805; colposcopy of the cervix with biopsy = 57454; endometrial biopsy = 58100; IUD insertion = 58300. For routine pregnancy supervision, use Z34.8x by trimester (not an O-code) when uncomplicated. Code cervical dysplasia to specificity (CIN I = N87.0, CIN II = N87.1). When one provider gives antepartum + delivery + postpartum care, use the global obstetric package (e.g., 59400) rather than itemizing visits.", "source": "OB/GYN Coding Guidance", "section": "Procedures"}, {"text": "Report the most extensive endoscopic service performed in a session: colonoscopy with snare polypectomy = 45385; colonoscopy with biopsy = 45380; diagnostic colonoscopy = 45378; EGD with biopsy = 43239; diagnostic EGD = 43235. Do NOT separately report the diagnostic scope (45378/43235) when a therapeutic procedure is done in the same session. Code the finding (e.g., colon polyp K63.5, gastritis K29.70); for a screening colonoscopy that finds a polyp, sequence the screening Z-code first.", "source": "GI Endoscopy Coding Guidance", "section": "Procedures"}, {"text": "Code the dermatologic procedure performed: shave/tangential biopsy = 11102; punch biopsy = 11104; destruction of a premalignant lesion (actinic keratosis), first lesion = 17000; destruction of benign lesions (e.g., warts), up to 14 = 17110. When a biopsy and a same-lesion destruction/excision are done together, the biopsy is bundled — report only the more extensive service. Code the lesion diagnosis (e.g., actinic keratosis L57.0, basal cell carcinoma C44.91); use 'uncertain behavior' (D48.5) when biopsying before a histologic diagnosis.", "source": "Dermatology Coding Guidance", "section": "Procedures"}, {"text": "Code the urologic procedure performed: ESWL lithotripsy = 50590; diagnostic cystourethroscopy = 52000; cystoscopy with bladder-tumor resection = 52234; needle prostate biopsy = 55700. Code the finding (calculus N20.x, bladder neoplasm C67.9, BPH N40.0/N40.1, hematuria R31.9). Diagnostic cystoscopy is bundled into a same-session therapeutic cystoscopy — do not report both.", "source": "Urology Coding Guidance", "section": "Procedures"}]}, {"hard": true, "notes": "Clean coding case with well-documented pathology-confirmed CIN II diagnosis and clearly stated colposcopy procedure with both cervical biopsy and endocervical curettage. No documentation gaps identified. The abnormal cervical cytology (HSIL) mentioned as indication is not separately coded as it represents the screening finding that led to the diagnostic procedure confirming the CIN II diagnosis.", "stage": "3_coding", "title": "Code Candidate Generation", "samples": 3, "candidates": [{"code": "N87.1", "role": "principal", "sequence": 1, "modifiers": [], "_agreement": 1.0, "confidence": 0.95, "code_system": "ICD10CM", "description": "Moderate cervical dysplasia (CIN II)", "chart_citations": [{"text": "Pathology returned moderate cervical dysplasia (CIN II)", "section": "FINDINGS", "line_end": 4, "line_start": 4}, {"text": "Moderate cervical dysplasia (CIN II)", "section": "IMPRESSION", "line_end": 5, "line_start": 5}], "rule_justification": "Pathology-confirmed moderate cervical dysplasia (CIN II) documented in findings and impression", "guideline_citations": [{"text": "Code cervical dysplasia to specificity (CIN I = N87.0, CIN II = N87.1)", "source": "OB/GYN Coding Guidance", "section": "Procedures"}]}, {"code": "57454", "role": "procedure", "sequence": 2, "modifiers": [], "_agreement": 1.0, "confidence": 0.95, "code_system": "CPT", "description": "Colposcopy of the cervix with biopsy(s) of the cervix and endocervical curettage", "chart_citations": [{"text": "Colposcopy of the cervix with cervical biopsy and endocervical curettage", "section": "PROCEDURE", "line_end": 3, "line_start": 3}], "rule_justification": "Colposcopy with both cervical biopsy and endocervical curettage explicitly documented", "guideline_citations": [{"text": "colposcopy of the cervix with biopsy = 57454", "source": "OB/GYN Coding Gui